## 📝 Project Report (Communication Case Study)

A common situation where poor digital communication causes real problems is when a student sends an urgent, frustrated email to a professor about a grade without a subject line, proper salutation, or clear context. For example, a student might simply write, "Why did I get a zero on this?" from a personal, unprofessional email address like 'skaterdude99@gmail.com'. 

This creates immediate friction. The professor doesn't know who the student is, which class they are referring to, or what assignment is in question, delaying resolution and creating a poor professional impression. 

This could be easily avoided by using a university-issued email address, writing a clear and specific subject line (e.g., "Question Regarding Module 2 Grade - CS101"), using a respectful greeting ("Dear Professor Smith,"), and calmly explaining the issue with necessary identifying details.
